 

 1. "uname — Print system/kernel information

 Syntax


uname [OPTION]


 Common Options (Explained Clearly)

  Option     Meaning                  Example       Output Description                                                                          
   -------    ---------------------    ----------    -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------   
   uname    Prints kernel name       uname       Usually Linux                                                                             
   -a       All information          uname -a    Kernel name, nodename, kernel release, version, machine, processor, hardware platform, OS   
   -s       Kernel name              uname -s    e.g., Linux                                                                               
   -n       Node/hostname            uname -n    e.g., server0                                                                             
   -r       Kernel release           uname -r    e.g., 5. 4.0-362.el9.x86_64                                                               
   -v       Kernel version           uname -v    Build date & time                                                                           
   -m       Machine hardware name    uname -m    e.g., x86_64, aarch64                                                                   
   -p       Processor type           uname -p    May show unknown                                                                          
   -i       Hardware platform        uname -i    e.g., x86_64                                                                              
   -o       Operating system         uname -o    Usually GNU/Linux                                                                         



 2. hostname — Show or set the system hostname

 Basic Usage


hostname

Shows current hostname.

 Useful Options

   Option                Description                     Example               
   ------------------    ----------------------------    -------------------   
   hostname            Show hostname                   hostname            
   hostname newname    Set new hostname (temporary)    hostname server0    
   -I                  Show all IP addresses           hostname -I         
   -f                  Show FQDN                       hostname -f         



 3. hostnamectl — Manage hostname and system info

 Purpose

Shows OS version, chassis, kernel, architecture, hostname, etc.

 Basic Command


hostnamectl


 Options

   Option                   Description                 Example                                              
   ---------------------    ------------------------    --------------------------------------------------   
   set-hostname <name>    Permanently set hostname    hostnamectl set-hostname web-server                
   --pretty               Set a “pretty name”         hostnamectl set-hostname "My Server" --pretty      
   --static               Set static hostname         hostnamectl set-hostname server0  --static         
   --transient            Temporary hostname          hostnamectl set-hostname temp-server --transient   

note: Pretty = More readable format.
      static = permanent 

 4. uptime — Shows uptime + load average

 Basic Command


uptime


 Typical Output


 4:32:59 up 3 days,  5: 0,  2 users,  load average: 0. 0, 0.05, 0.0 


 Meaning

 up 3 days → system has been running for 3 days
 2 users → logged-in users
 load average

   last   min, 5 min,  5 min CPU load
   <   = healthy
   > CPU count = overloaded



 5. uptime -p — Pretty uptime

 Usage


uptime -p


 Output


up 3 days, 5 hours


note: Pretty = More readable format.



 6. whoami — Shows current logged user

 Usage


whoami

Returns your effective username.

Example:
root




 7. who — Shows currently logged-in users

 Usage


who


 Example Output


rohit   pts/0    2025-0 -26  0: 2 ( 92. 68. . 0)


 Fields Meaning

 username
 terminal (pts/0)
 login date/time
 source IP

 Useful Options

   Option      Description        Example    
   --------    ---------------    --------   
   who -b    Last boot time     who -b   
   who -H    Add header         who -H   
   who -q    Number of users    who -q   

---

 8. w — Detailed logged-in user activity

 Usage


w


 What it shows

 username
 TTY
 remote IP
 login time
 idle time
 JCPU
 PCPU
 current process (what user is doing)

 Useful Options

   Option    Description     Example   
   ------    ------------    -------   
   w -h    No header       w -h    
   w -f    Show from IP    w -f    

---

 9. id — Return user identity info

 Basic Usage


id


 Output Example


uid= 000(rohit) gid= 000(rohit) groups= 000(rohit), 0(wheel)


 Meaning

 UID → User ID
 GID → Group ID
 groups → All groups user belongs to

 Options

   Option      Description          
   --------    ------------------   
   id -u     Show UID             
   id -g     Show GID             
   id -G     Show all group IDs   
   id -un    Show only username   
   id -gn    Show group name      

---

  10. timedatectl — Time, UTC, NTP settings

 Basic Usage


timedatectl


 Shows

 Local time
 Universal time
 RTC time
 Timezone
 NTP enabled/active
 DST

 Useful Options

   Option                  Description           Example                                        
   --------------------    ------------------    --------------------------------------------   
   list-timezones        Show all timezones    timedatectl list-timezones                   
   set-timezone TZ       Set timezone          timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Kolkata        
   set-ntp true/false    Enable/disable NTP    timedatectl set-ntp true                     
   set-time              Set system time       timedatectl set-time "2025-0 -30  0:30:00"   

---

11. date — Display or set system date/time

 Usage


date


 Example Output


Thu Jan 30  4:25: 0 IST 2025


 Formatting Options

   Option                Description    Example        
   ------------------    -----------    ------------   
   date "+%Y-%m-%d"    YYYY-MM-DD     2025-0 -30   
   date "+%H:%M:%S"    HH:MM:SS        4:30:55     
   date -u             UTC time       date -u      

 Set system date/time (manual)


sudo date -s "2025-0 -30  0: 5:00"

